column17: ORS had no tag - it is the 4th ORS from the left side - there were two cages attched to one another, when I pulled them up, the bottom one detached and fell into the water - it looked empty however

This is a recount.  I last counted this on 8/15 about 9 weeks ago.  The ORS was crammed with oysters and a a few sea squirts and really difficult to lift.  On 6/27 the weight was from algae and not sea squirts. There's also a lot of oysters here and was concerned I wouldn't get them all back in. I did get them all back in, but it wasn't easy.  I remember last time I had the same concern but it was far easier to get them back in.  There were several oysters over 105cm.  I threw them overboard.  I don't remember how many I tossed. Cage was reasonable to lift.  There were a lot of sea squits.  It has a very long rope so must be on the river floor often.  I was surprised it wasn't heavily silted as it was previously.  While I noted previously there were blue mussels and no ribbed mussels, now there are no blue mussels and many small ribbed mussels.  I saw two slipper shells which is unusual but the amount of spat was awesome. I began measuring them until I realized they would totally throw off the comparison so I counted them but did not measure them. Before I stopped measuring them I had measured 10 and thus added 10 more to the count.  In the count, measured spats are replaced with non-spat oysters. There were 4 spat oysters on the cage which I did not try to remove.

I saw two slipper shells which is unusual but the amount of spat was awesome. I began measuring them until I realized they would totally throw off the comparison so I counted them but did not measure them. Before I stopped measuring them I had measured 10 and thus added 10 more to the count.  In the count, measured spats are replaced with non-spat oysters. There were 4 spat oysters on the cage which I did not try to remove.

There were 4 spat oysters on the cage which I did not try to remove.
